These panels are very loosely based on the real ones, they have the
right text and most of the holes, but do not match 100% by a long
shot. I strongly suggest before commiting to acrylic cuts, you do
tests in card or paper first and test you are happy, and if not modify
the design as needed. Time permitting I will also try help you,
contact me at the email above.
Please enjoy, and happy SimPit building, please send me pictures of
your work so I can see my hard work being put to use :)
Instructions:
1) All panels have 3 main layers, Top, Middle and Bottom. These contain all
objects which need to be sent to your chosen machine to cut the material.
2) I use a K40 laser (with K40 Whisperer software) with the following
materials and settings:
Bottom Layer: 3mm or 5mm Clear Acrylic. 17mA laser power, 3x cut passes
Middle Layer: 3mm Opaque (Opal) acrylic, 17ma laser power, 3x cut passes
Top Layer: 3mm pure white acrylic, 17mA laser power, 3x cut passes, 1x
raster engrave pass at 200mm/s
3) To produce a panel, begin by hiding all other layers except for the panel
you wish to create (Locked layers do not matter). Then hide all layers except
the layer you wish to cut (start Bottom>Top), finally go to Edit>Select All in
All Layers.
This should now highlight all objects in the layer, press Ctrl+C to copy the
objects, in a new Inkscape file press Ctrl+V to paste them. Go to
File>Document Properties>Resize to Content to reduce the document size to
match the panel, this really (really) helps with allignment in your laser.
Save the file, and send it over to your laser, and cut. Pro tip, as you remove
parts from the laser, with a sharpie add a small letter to the top side of the
cut piece, it's very easy to screw up and place on upside down during
assembly.
4) Assembly: Rinse and repeat the above to produce all the panels you wish.
Now to assemble, you will need to "bond" the top and middle layer together
with an Acrylic Cement, there are dozens on Amazon and any will probably
work if it mentions Acrylic. Start by removing any protective films on the
acrylic top and middle layers (on the surfaces that will touch, leave the
others on for protection until ready to paint), then do a test alignment by
placing the top layer on top of the middle layer, be absulutely certain you're
happy with how it looks and everything aligns, once you do this next bit
there's no coming back.
Take your acrylic cement (it'll look and smell like isopropyalcohol), and using
a syringe suck up a couple ml, and carefully apply a thin layer evenly across
the top of the middle layer, then quickly but carefully place the top layer on,
you will have around 20s ish to get it aligned properly, so don't panic, you
should be able to push them around during this time. Leave it to set for at
least 15min, if not they may come apart when moved, waiting an hour+ is
recommended.
5) Painting: Stack all of your panel layers (for a single panel) together and in
order (Bottom>top), ensuring you remove any protective films, and spray
paint the entire stack in one go with Matt Black paint. Start with a thin layer,
wait 10min, then apply 3-4 (or 5) decent layers (don't go nuts, it'll run)
allowing 20min between each layer. If it's cold where you are, then allow the
spray paint can to sit in hot water (40c) for around 10min before you begin,
if not the paint may "sputter" out of the can.
6) Engraving: Now your panels are cut and painted (and dry!), take the top
layer of the panel you wish to engrave and do the same process as above,
copy all the objects from that layer and paste in to a new file and then load
in to your laser software.
You need to be 100% certain on the alignment of the panel in the laser here,
believe me you'll ruin many panels at this stage. Once aligned, double check
your laser power and speed settings for raster engrave, and then hit the go
button. Fingers crossed, everything is aligned, the panel is the right way
around, and your laser goes ahead and engraves some beautiful text for
you.
7) Enjoy, you should now be ready to start fitting components. Please see
my components file for a list of what I used, and what this file is designed
around.
8) On the right I have included reference objects for all layers, simply copy
and paste (unlock the layer) them and move each part of the object to the
correct layer as needed.
